<br>
  Robert Park is the chairman of the American Physical Society.  He's an anti-manned space program gasbag.  He's trying to butt snorkle his way on to the post Columbia tragedy advisory committee, so he can spin his BS.  It'll be a sad day if the idiot gets on the committee.  Park's vision of space exploration/development is robots.  Period.  <br>
  I agree with you about O'Keefe.  I think he's doing a pretty good job, given the state NASA was in after moron Goldin left.  <br>
  You know, Hamster, here's my two cents on where the U.S. needs to go in space.<br>
<br>
1.  U.S. Congress should create a 1 billion dollar prize for the first company to get launch costs to $100 dollar per pound.<br>
2.  Privatize all (only to U.S. companies) U.S. launch efforts.  That includes the Space Shuttle.  Also, ban ArianeSpace from launching any American payloads (yeah, I'm being petty, but I hate the limp &lt;blank&gt; French).  I always liked the space/high altitude billboard advertising concept a few years ago.  There was actually a plan to have a space billboard orbit over the 1996 Atlanta Olympics I believe.  Of course, the eco-wackos hated the idea.<br>
3.  Commercialize the International Space Station to every extent possible.  SUPPORT space tourism.<br>
4.  Get NASA out of near Earth orbit.  Have NASA team up with a commercial firm to mine an asteroid, mine the moon, put a radio telescope on the moon, go to Mars, build a space station at L5, anything, but work in near Earth orbit.<br>
5.  We need to look at SPS; Solar Power Stations and Beamed Power Vehicles (read some of Leik Myrabo's work) more closely.<br>
6.  Build a space based missile defense system.<br>
<br>
  I dream big. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>spacefaring rodent</span><br>  Posts: 1097<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/5/03 12:00 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=823.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Village Idiot</span><hr size=1> I'm definately all for the commercialization of space.  I think our grandest goal as far as space is concerned is learning how to colonize it and exploit its resources.  There's so many good ideas I've read out there by private companies.  Even though I don't think this particular company has a chance in hell of financially pulling it off I think <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.spaceislandgroup.com">Space Island Group</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> has a lot of very technically feasible and good ideas for how we could go about doing things in space.  Their space stations based on coupling the external tanks of the shuttle together into a large ring seem to make a lot more sense and would be inherently more useful and spacious than that near worthless political stunt the ISS.    <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>4. Get NASA out of near Earth orbit. Have NASA team up with a commercial firm to mine an asteroid, mine the moon, put a radio telescope on the moon, go to Mars, build a space station at L5, anything, but work in near Earth orbit.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I agree with this entirely, NASA shouldn't be left in charge of managing routine operations of spacecraft that only go to orbit.  They should be a pure research institution that can buy use of vehicles in the private sector.  The only way to reduce launch costs is to promote real competition and get away from this &quot;cost maximizing&quot; nonsense that the government engages in.  That billion dollar prize might not be such a bad idea even if the government seeks to kill incentives for private enterprise as a whole to get to orbit and beyond (the UN would certainly love to keep private companies out of space as they proved when they scrambled to amend the space treaty with a provision that would do just that.  Thankgod that particular provision didn't go through because, ironically, the Soviet Union and the USA didn't sign on.) <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A> at: 3/5/03 12:02:00 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=megaloman84>Megaloman84</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 36<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/5/03 1:11 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=823.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Village Idiot</span><hr size=1> Back to the genesis of this thread,<br>
<br>
You guys make it sound like opposition to the Shuttle/Station program is a bad thing.  I agree that limiting space exploration to robots is retarded, but let's face it, the Shuttle and ISS are deadend routes to nowhere.<br>
<br>
Opposition to NASA largesse is fine in my oppinion if the alternative espoused is a more aggressive and efficient space program.<br>
<br>
I like the idea of prohibiting NASA from conducting routine orbital operations.  There is nothing that can be done in orbit that the private sector can't do better.  NASA should be out on the far edge of the human space initiative pioneering new technologies and new techniques and pushing the envelope of our capability is space.  They should be on Mars, on NEOs and even in the main belt and the outer planetary systems.<br>
<br>
As far as the idea of offering prizes for private accomplishment,  I think it is probably the best dollar value that a government space effort could get.  Not only will private firms accomplish the stated objectives faster, better and cheaper than NASA could, they will ultimately spend more money on development than the posted prize money.<br>
<br>
Look at all the R&amp;D that the various x-prize contenders are conducting. All told, far more than the $10 million will go into new technologies and craft as a result of a rather modest incentive.  The $25,000 Orteig prize that fueled the race to cross the Atlantic back in the 20s resulted in various groups spending a combined total of more than $400,000 on aviation development.<br>
<br>
Given this, there is no need to limit our prizes to a single incentive for cheap access for orbit.  We could set up rewards for all sort of feats, from landing a crew on mars and keeping them there a minimum specified period of time, to sending a probe through an as-of-yet unheard of deltaV  or any other sort of accomplishment that would have desirable consequences.<br>
<br>
Once private companies reach any of these goals, the technology will be available for NASA to use in an ongoing program of space exploration.  One of the reasons that the Russians were able to consistantly best us in space with inferior equipment and funding was that they were more focused on capability than just technology.  It doesn't make sense to have NASA spend most of it's resources constantly developing new technology when they havn't even made a real effort to use the technology we already have.  <br>
<br>
Comparatively small incentives could be offered to the private sector for independant technology development with the potential for lucrative NASA contracts once the technology come to fruition.  This could spawn a whole new kind of space industry and pave the way for truely large-scale private development of space.      <br>
<br>
This subject is treated in more depth in <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>The Case For Mars</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> by Bob Zubrin.  He talks at length about this model for space exploration.<br>
